00:00:57.690 --> 00:00:59.847
engaging live ops
events in your games.

00:01:02.980 --> 00:01:08.490
So, what is LiveOps and
why is it important?

00:01:08.490 --> 00:01:12.600
Put very simply, LiveOps is
running games as a service.

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:16.200
This means that your games
become a living, breathing,

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:19.500
organic product that
is constantly changing,

00:01:19.500 --> 00:01:22.710
giving your new users a
brand new experience each

00:01:22.710 --> 00:01:25.170
and every single day.

00:01:25.170 --> 00:01:28.950
The goals of LiveOps are to
augment engagement, stimulate

00:01:28.950 --> 00:01:32.316
monetization, and
prevent player churn.

00:01:32.316 --> 00:01:33.690
So, let's dig a
little bit deeper

00:01:33.690 --> 00:01:35.562
into how to actually
achieve these goals.

00:01:38.730 --> 00:01:42.300
As you guys are already
aware, content is king.

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:45.210
New content is what keeps
your players actively

00:01:45.210 --> 00:01:48.960
playing and actively
spending in your games.

00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:51.900
The players who devote
the most time in your game

00:01:51.900 --> 00:01:55.560
become your loyal fans
and your best advocates.

00:01:55.560 --> 00:01:58.560
These are the players who
have higher retention rates

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:00.930
and higher session frequency.

00:02:00.930 --> 00:02:04.920
Now, Kabam, has lovingly coined
these players the regulars,

00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:07.560
but for all you
Norm Peterson fans

00:02:07.560 --> 00:02:09.769
out there-- anyone who
knows what "Cheers"

00:02:09.769 --> 00:02:14.130
is-- it's the Norm Petersons.

00:02:14.130 --> 00:02:17.100
High engagement and
retention are the keys

00:02:17.100 --> 00:02:20.040
to creating long
term lifetime value,

00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:23.760
because in the world of
mobile gaming content is king.

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:29.130
And that means that time
on device equals money.

00:02:29.130 --> 00:02:31.590
Your most active
and engaged players

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:34.120
are more likely to
have higher LTV curves.

00:02:36.870 --> 00:02:38.700
So, another way to
think about LiveOps

00:02:38.700 --> 00:02:42.060
is the strategic distribution
of content through time

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:44.290
limited sales and events.

00:02:44.290 --> 00:02:47.490
Now, when we talk about content
in the context of LiveOps,

00:02:47.490 --> 00:02:51.630
we're not talking about large
APK updates and client side

00:02:51.630 --> 00:02:52.740
features.

00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:55.530
It can be small,
server side changes.

00:02:55.530 --> 00:02:58.080
For example, adding
a weekend tournament,

00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:01.650
or temporarily changing the
drop rates in a dungeon,

00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:04.470
introducing a brand
new hero character

00:03:04.470 --> 00:03:09.510
or a new piece of legendary
gear into your gaming economy.

00:03:09.510 --> 00:03:12.270
This new content is
delivered in mobile games

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:16.950
through two different
channels-- sales and events.

00:03:16.950 --> 00:03:20.130
When you sell content through
a gotcha or IAP bundles,

00:03:20.130 --> 00:03:24.180
you drive monetization metrics,
such as new buyer conversion,

00:03:24.180 --> 00:03:25.860
or ARPU.

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:29.520
But using content as the chase
prize in a competitive event

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:32.535
can help you drive
engagement metrics like log

00:03:32.535 --> 00:03:36.300
in velocity or session length.

00:03:36.300 --> 00:03:39.840
Making small server side
changes to your game

00:03:39.840 --> 00:03:43.230
or strategically cadencing
small pieces of new content

00:03:43.230 --> 00:03:46.170
that are hidden within
your large APK updates

00:03:46.170 --> 00:03:48.930
keeps the player
experience fresh.

00:03:48.930 --> 00:03:50.814
But why is all of
this important?

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:56.130
Kabam's CEO, Kevin
Chou, recently

00:03:56.130 --> 00:03:59.430
wrote an article for
GamesIndustry.biz describing

00:03:59.430 --> 00:04:04.020
the mobile game revenue curve
that he calls the shark fin.

00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:06.180
This occurs when
a mobile game is

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:09.120
released without a consistent
pipeline of content

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:11.040
to keep users busy.

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:15.900
As you guys know, mobile
gamers love to consume content,

00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:20.070
but they also get
bored really easily.

00:04:20.070 --> 00:04:24.270
All your new content is
bundled into large APK updates,

00:04:24.270 --> 00:04:26.670
but releasing that
content all at once

00:04:26.670 --> 00:04:29.640
leads to rapid
content consumption.

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:32.160
Once a player runs through
all the new content,

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:35.770
they eventually get bored and
then churn out of your game.

00:04:35.770 --> 00:04:37.890
This means that each
of your new updates

00:04:37.890 --> 00:04:40.860
is reaching fewer
and fewer players,

00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:43.530
and the revenue bumps that
you see from these new updates

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:47.700
diminish over time, creating
these smaller and smaller shark

00:04:47.700 --> 00:04:49.830
fins.

00:04:49.830 --> 00:04:52.530
In his article, Kevin
points to LiveOps

00:04:52.530 --> 00:04:55.950
as a way to minimize
this revenue degradation.

00:04:55.950 --> 00:04:58.560
LiveOps limited time
sales and events

00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:01.290
can help you slow
roll the content held

00:05:01.290 --> 00:05:05.730
within your large APK updates
and thereby helping you avoid

00:05:05.730 --> 00:05:10.380
the shark fin, and
instead helps to drive

00:05:10.380 --> 00:05:12.740
a steady and consistent
heartbeat of revenue.

00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:18.220
But it's also important to
note that LiveOps is not

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:20.770
about short term revenue gains.

00:05:20.770 --> 00:05:24.040
When executed properly,
the strategy behind LiveOps

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:26.470
is to engage and
retain your users,

00:05:26.470 --> 00:05:31.630
to create healthy long
term lifetime value.

00:05:31.630 --> 00:05:35.820
So, to recap, LiveOps is
running games as a service.

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:38.890
It's a strategic distribution
of content through time

00:05:38.890 --> 00:05:41.470
limited sales and events.

00:05:41.470 --> 00:05:43.630
A consistent stream
of new content

00:05:43.630 --> 00:05:46.480
will help you augment
engagement, stimulate

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:49.840
monetization, and
prevent player churn.

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:53.920
And, finally, a happy and
engaged gaming community

00:05:53.920 --> 00:05:56.230
drives consistent
healthy revenue

00:05:56.230 --> 00:05:59.080
along with higher LTV curves
to help you get the most

00:05:59.080 --> 00:06:01.870
out of your UA budgets.

00:06:01.870 --> 00:06:03.850
So, by now, you
guys are probably

00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:05.950
ready to see some
real world examples

00:06:05.950 --> 00:06:07.990
of these engaging
LiveOps events.

